A @comparison of how textbooks teach mathematical problem solving in Japan and the United States
Richard E. Mayer and Valerie Sims ; Hidetsugu Tajika
publ. by the American Educational Research Association

This brief report compared the lesson on addition and subtraction of signed whole numbers in three seventh-grade Japanese mathematics textbooks with the corresponding lesson in four U.S. mathematics textbooks. The results indicated that Japanese books contained many more worked-out examples and relevant illustrations than did the U.S. books, whereas the U.S. books contained roughly as many exercises and many more irrelevant illustrations than did the Japanese books.
